{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f744b07d-2171-4f0b-8d96-7ad8fc9a4030","content":"The project doesn't exist in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command: \"dotnet\"`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your server.\n- **`${workspaceFolder}`** — resolves to your VS Code workspace root.\n- If your server uses **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use `\"type\": \"sse\"` with a `\"url\"` field pointing to the server endpoint.\n\nMake sure your C# MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio protocol). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, the `StdioServerTransport` handles this automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"432fc8e4-860a-4297-aa8f-21db73010f1a","outputTokens":315,"requestId":"D029:F7CCA:157A5C4:17F5C58:6A0673BA"},"id":"747dc4dc-149e-4302-a806-50b873f63ccf","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:15:46.815Z","parentId":"2e8de53e-f837-4c8e-b126-675847ae97c0"}
